04217nam a22006855i 9780824863340DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248633407 a10.1515/97808248633402doi  a(DE-B1597)484626  a(OCoLC)1041976488  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aBIO0180002bisacsh0483pa290qDE-10100aLetting Go :bThe Story of Zen Master Tosui. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Japanese Zen in the Age of Tōsui -- tAbout the Translation -- tTribute to the Life of Zen Master Tōsui -- tBiographical Addendum:Tōsui’s Story -- tAppendix: Biography of Master Tōsui (Tōsui oshō den) -- tNotes to Text -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf the many eccentric figures in Japanese Zen, the Soto Zen master Tosui Unkei (d. 1683) is surely among the most colorful and extreme. Variously compared to Ryokan and Francis of Assisi, Tosui has been called "the original hippie." After many grueling years of Zen study and the sanction of a distinguished teacher, Tosui abandoned the religious establishment and became a drifter.The arresting details of Tosui's life were recorded in the Tribute (Tosui osho densan), a lively and colloquial account written by the celebrated scholar and Soto Zen master Menzan Zuiho. Menzan concentrates on Tosui's years as a beggar and laborer, recounting episodes from an unorthodox life while at the same time opening a new window on seventeenth-century Japan. The Tribute is translated here for the first time, accompanied by woodblock prints commissioned for the original 1768 edition. Peter Haskel's introduction places Tosui in the context of the Japanese Zen of his period--a time when the identities of early modern Zen schools were still being formed and a period of spiritual crisis for many distinguished monks who believed that the authentic Zen transmission had long ceased to exist. A biographical addendum offers a detailed overview of Tosui's life in light of surviving premodern sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aZen priestszJapanvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aHaskel, Peter.1 aRyōki, Zōsan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZuihō, Menzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486334040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863340423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824863340/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK